 the failure of the United States to prioritize a sufficient social wage for poor families outside of labor markets? The New Welfare Consensus offers a comprehensive look at welfare in the United States and how it has evolved in the last few decades. Darren Barany examines the origins of American antiwelfarism and traces how, over time, fundamentally conservative ideas became the dominant way of thinking about the welfare state, work, family, and personal responsibility, resulting in a paternalistic and stingy system of welfare programs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPublic welfarezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWelfare recipientsxEmploymentzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWelfare statezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aHistory : American History. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Sociology. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 4aSociology : Sociology of Work. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438470566423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438470566/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles